        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nineteen, adrift at City College, when he saw a cyclist hit on Ocean Avenue. The moments before the ambulance arrived were pure chaos. Then, the medics cut through the noise, their movements economical and sure. Watching them work on the asphalt, bringing order to the unthinkable, Marco felt a jolt of clarity. The abstract world of his textbooks dissolved. He saw a tangible way to matter, a clear purpose calling to him from the scream of that first siren. From that day, his path was set.\n\n2.\nHe remembers the scent of redwood dust in their foggy Sunset backyard. At sixteen, he was clumsy, helping his father build a small deck. He recalls the quiet concentration in his father\u2019s hands, showing him how to measure once and cut precisely. \"Mano firme, mente firme,\" his dad had said without looking up\u2014a steady hand, a steady mind. That afternoon, sanding a rough edge smooth, Marco learned the philosophy of quiet craft that would later guide him through the frantic, trembling moments of a stranger\u2019s worst day.\n\n3.\nIt was 3 AM in the Excelsior, rain drumming on the ambulance roof. The woman was terrified, the baby coming too fast. He locked eyes with her, his voice a low, reassuring anchor, and minutes later, he was holding a new, wailing life. In the dim light, with the city asleep outside, the world shrank to that sacred, primal moment. He felt not like a paramedic, but a conduit for something profound. That memory of life\u2019s pure force became a touchstone he\u2019d hold against the darkness for years.\n\n4.\nThe Bay Bridge pileup wasn\u2019t one call; it was a sprawling, metallic beast roaring in the fog. Moving from one mangled car to the next, triage tags in hand, he felt his practiced calm cracking. The scale of it was insurmountable, the radio chatter a litany of despair. He wasn't a healer; he was just cataloging a disaster. That night, for the first time, he felt the immense weight of the city break him. It was the shift that convinced him he couldn\u2019t carry it alone anymore.\n\n5.\nJust last week, on the 38 Geary heading home. The bus was warm, the evening drizzle streaking the windows. He watched the city slide by\u2014shoppers on Clement, the marquee of the Balboa Theatre, faces lit by phones. No sirens, no urgency. He was just another passenger, an anonymous part of the city\u2019s gentle, evening pulse. A quiet contentment settled over him. He was no longer fighting the city\u2019s crises, but was simply woven into its fabric, and it was finally enough."
